04043nam a22005535i 9780774819374DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20112010xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748193747 a10.59962/97807748193742doi  a(DE-B1597)662019  a(OCoLC)766417951  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE99.O45.S88 2011eb 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a971.31 aSunseri, Lina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeing Again of One Mind :bOneida Women and the Struggle for Decolonization /cLina Sunseri. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2010  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWomen and Indigenous Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tTheorizing Nations and Nationalisms: From Modernist to Indigenous Perspectives -- tA History of the Oneida Nation: From Creation Story to the Present -- tStruggles of Independence: From a Colonial Existence toward a Decolonized Nation -- tWomen, Nation, and National Identity: Oneida Women Standing Up and Speaking about Matters of the Nation -- tDreaming of a Free, Peaceful, Balanced Decolonized Nation: Being Again of One Mind -- tConcluding Remarks -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBeing Again of One Mind combines the narratives of Oneida women of various generations with a critical reading of feminist literature on nationalism to reveal that some Indigenous women view nationalism in the form of decolonization as a way to restore traditional gender balance and well-being to their own lives and communities. By giving a voice to Oneida women's thoughts on tradition and nation, this book challenges mainstream feminist ideas about the masculine bias of Western theories of nation and about the dangers of nationalist movements that idealize women's so-called traditional role. Lina Sunseri shows that feminist insights, although useful to many women's and feminist groups, cannot be applied universally to all women or to societies with traditional forms of nation based on good relations between men and women. Oneida women do not view nationalism as a threat but rather as a way for women and men to be again of one mind.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aMonture, Patricia A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077481937440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774819374423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774819374/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles